);

Context("Numeric");
$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;

@which = NchooseK(3,3);
@plane = ( $which[0], $which[1] );
num_sort( @plane );

@axes = ('x', 'y', 'z');
$x = $axes[$plane[0]];
$y = $axes[$plane[1]];
$z = $axes[$which[2]];
$xy = "$x$y";

$uvec = ('i', 'j', 'k')[$which[2]];
$r0 = random(2,5,1);

$flux = Compute( "pi*$r0^4/2" );

Context()->texStrings;
TEXT(beginproblem());
BEGIN_TEXT

Calculate the flux of the vector field
\( \vec F=($x^2+$y^2)\vec $uvec \) through the disk of radius $r0
in the \( $xy \)-plane and centered at the origin and oriented upward.

$PAR
flux = \{ ans_rule(35) \}

END_TEXT
Context()->normalStrings;

ANS( $flux->cmp() );

$fd = ( $r0 == 2 || $r0 == 4 ) ? ($r0**4/2) . "\pi" :
    "\frac{" . ($r0**4) . "\pi}{2}";

Context()->texStrings;
SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION'));
$PAR SOLUTION $PAR

Since the disk, \(D\), is in the \($xy\)-plane and oriented upward,
\(d\vec A=\vec $uvec\, d$x\, d$y\) and
\[ \int_{D} \vec F\cdot d\vec A = 
   \int_{D} ($x^2+$y^2)\vec $uvec\cdot \vec $uvec\,
       d$x\,d$y = 
   \int_{D}($x^2+$y^2)\, d$x\,d$y.\]
Using polar coordinates (with \($x = r\cos\theta\) and \($y = r\sin\theta\)),
\[ \int_{D}\vec F\cdot d\vec A = 
   \int_0^{2\pi}\int_0^{$r0} r^2\cdot r\, dr\,d\theta =
   2\pi \left.\frac {r^4}4\right|_0^{$r0} = $fd.
\]


END_SOLUTION
Context()->normalStrings;

COMMENT('Uses MathObjects');

